   =20
 =20
There it is:Paramount Global agreed to merge with Skydance Media in a deal =
that hands control of the storied Hollywood studio to producer David Elliso=
n, ending one of the industry=E2=80=99s most dramatic acquisitions.As part =
of the complicated deal months in the making, Paramount Chair Shari Redston=
e agreed to sell her family=E2=80=99s National Amusements Inc., which contr=
ols about 77% of the voting stock in Paramount, for $2.4 billion, according=
 to a statement released by the company Sunday.The accord marks an abrupt t=
urnaround after talks between Redstone and Ellison, the son of Oracle Corp.=
 co-founder Larry Ellison, collapsed last month. Redstone=E2=80=99s decisio=
n at the time to end discussions shocked the board and frustrated employees=
 and investors, sending the stock tumbling.=C2=A0The Ellison family and Red=
Bird Capital Partners have agreed to invest more than $8 billion in the bus=
iness. That includes $1.5 billion to help pay down Paramount=E2=80=99s debt=
 and $4.5 billion to buy Paramount shares.I suppose you can think of this d=
eal as having three main parts:=09The Skydance investors buy National Amuse=
ments to get control of Paramount. National Amusements owns roughly 10% of =
the stock of Paramount, but Paramount has two share classes: Class A stock,=
 which has voting rights, and Class B, which doesn=E2=80=99t. And National =
Amusements owns=C2=A0roughly 77% of the voting Class A stock.=C2=A0So the S=
kydance consortium pays Redstone $2.4 billion for National Amusements, and =
it gets voting control of Paramount.=09Paramount then acquires Skydance: Pa=
ramount will merge with Skydance, giving Skydance some shares of new Paramo=
unt. This deal values Skydance at $4.75 billion, and Skydance gets paid in =
new (nonvoting)=C2=A0Paramount stock at $15 per share.=09The Skydance inves=
tors also kick in another $6 billion of cash to buy Paramount shares: They =
buy $1.5 billion of stock (nonvoting stock at $15 per share) directly from =
Paramount to strengthen the balance sheet, and another $4.5 billion from Pa=
ramount=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shareholders. The $4.5 billion goes first to=C2=A0no=
n-Redstone holders of=C2=A0voting=C2=A0Paramount shares, at=C2=A0$23 per sh=
are, for a total of up to $211 million, though they can choose to roll over=
 into new Paramount stock instead. (In which case they will get 1.53=C2=A0n=
onvoting Class B shares of the new company per Class A share of the old com=
pany: In any case, the Skydance investors will end up with 100% of the voti=
ng stock.)=C2=A0And then the rest of the cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $4.3 bil=
lion =E2=80=94=C2=A0goes to=C2=A0buying=C2=A0nonvoting Class B shares at $1=
5 per share. If every Paramount shareholder elects cash, then only about 43=
% of them will get cashed out.
  [1]
=C2=A0The rest will keep their nonvoting Class B stock in the new Paramount=
. As of noon today, Paramount=E2=80=99s Class B shares were trading around=
=C2=A0$11.47, so presumably everyone will elect cash and get prorated.Those=
 elements are sort of in declining order of importance. Step 1 is really th=
e main thing: You can=E2=80=99t do anything with Paramount without Shari Re=
dstone=E2=80=99s voting shares, and that means buying her out at a premium.=
 And then=C2=A0buying out Redstone gives you control of Paramount. If you w=
ant to take over Paramount, make yourself chief executive officer and gener=
ally take control of its strategy, buying a block of 77% of the voting stoc=
k gets you most of the way there.But Step 2 is also important to making the=
 deal make sense for Skydance: They want to integrate their company with Pa=
ramount. The investor presentation touts the benefits of =E2=80=9Cunificati=
on of marquee rights=E2=80=9D (because Paramount and Skydance co-produce va=
rious franchises like Top Gun, Mission: Impossible and Star Trek) and trans=
itioning =E2=80=9Cto a world-class media and technology enterprise.=E2=80=
=9D Also it is optically appealing for this deal to involve a merger of two=
 actual content companies, instead of just a group of investors taking over=
 Paramount without paying for all of the shares.And Step 3 is important to =
getting the deal through a special committee of independent Paramount direc=
tors. The deal makes sense for Redstone and Skydance with only Steps 1 and =
2: Redstone would get her cash, and Skydance would get its merger and its c=
ontrol of Paramount, without paying any of Paramount=E2=80=99s other shareh=
olders anything. But Paramount=E2=80=99s board of directors has fiduciary o=
bligations to the nonvoting shareholders, and it wants them to get somethin=
g too. Cashing out=C2=A0all=C2=A0of them at a premium would be too big an a=
sk, but cashing out=C2=A0almost half=C2=A0of their stock, at a premium, is =
a compromise the board can live with. =E2=80=9CWe are pleased to have reach=
ed an agreement that we believe delivers to Paramount stockholders both imm=
ediate value and future upside opportunity,=E2=80=9D said the special commi=
ttee.Meanwhile Redstone is getting roughly $2.4 billion for National Amusem=
ents (including debt), which owns about 31.5 million Class A shares and abo=
ut 32 million Class B shares. At the deal prices ($23 per Class A share, $1=
5 per Class B), National Amusements=E2=80=99 stake in Paramount is worth ab=
out $1.2 billion. The extra $1.2 billion presumably accounts for National A=
musements=E2=80=99 chain of movie theaters, which are worth something. But =
it also presumably accounts for=C2=A0an extra premium for Redstone, who is =
essential to the deal, and whose Class A shares are just worth more=C2=A0th=
an everyone else=E2=80=99s. The other Class A shareholders have=C2=A0votes,=
 but she has the votes that matter.
