      Private credit
   =20
 =20
Here is a crude stylized history of the=C2=A0development of private credit
  [4]
:=09Once, companies (and private equity sponsors) borrowed money either fro=
m banks=C2=A0or in the bond market.=09=E2=80=9CFrom banks,=E2=80=9D in that=
 sentence, is a bit misleading: A lot of bank loans (particularly leveraged=
 loans to fund private equity buyouts) are syndicated broadly to non-bank i=
nvestors. Banks don=E2=80=99t just lend from their balance sheets and hold =
loans to maturity; they are largely in the moving business, not the storage=
 business.=09Then private credit was invented: Asset managers=C2=A0raised l=
ong-term locked-up funds from institutional investors, and they used those =
funds to make loans to companies (and private equity sponsors) directly, by=
passing banks and the bond market.=09Then private credit funds were like =
=E2=80=9Cwell this is fine, but it would be even better if, instead of usin=
g our investors=E2=80=99 money to make loans, we could borrow some money to=
 fund the loans.=E2=80=9D Instead of taking $100 of investor money, lending=
 it out at 10%, and passing on the 10% returns to the investors, you take $=
100 of investor money=C2=A0plus $100 of borrowed money that costs 8%, you l=
end it out at 10%, you pay back your interest cost and you pass on 12% retu=
rns to your investors.=C2=A0=09Banks were like =E2=80=9Cyes that sounds gre=
at.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Lending to private credit funds is a way to make up for t=
he business that private credit funds took from the banks: Private credit f=
unds now compete with banks to make buyout loans, and when the private cred=
it funds win those deals, the banks miss out on fees. But the banks can get=
 some of the business back by lending to the private credit funds. Also, le=
nding to private credit funds is structurally less=C2=A0risky=C2=A0for the =
banks than doing the buyout loans themselves: If the buyout goes bust and c=
an=E2=80=99t repay its loans, the private credit funds take the first loss =
and the bank has a senior position.=09But banks still are in the moving bus=
iness, not the storage business.=09So eventually they ask questions like =
=E2=80=9Cwhat if we syndicated our loans to private credit funds, so that w=
e don=E2=80=99t have to hold them on our balance sheet=E2=80=9D?And so you =
get this, from Christopher Whittall at IFR:Citigroup is working on securing=
 credit ratings for senior loans it makes to direct lenders to create more =
of a syndicated market where the bank can distribute these exposures to a w=
ider range of investors.The move comes amid a mushrooming in private credit=
 markets over the past decade, coupled with a sharp rise in the amount of f=
inancing that banks provide to direct lending funds so they can leverage th=
eir portfolios of loans to middle-market companies.The plans to encourage m=
ore investors to put their money into these senior loan facilities shows ho=
w banks=E2=80=99 financing desks are struggling to keep pace with the rapid=
 expansion of direct lending =E2=80=93 and how these funds are becoming mor=
e deeply intertwined with the broader financial system.=E2=80=9CPrivate cre=
dit markets are growing at 8%=E2=80=9310% a year, but bank balance sheets c=
learly aren=E2=80=99t growing at that rate,=E2=80=9D said Mickey Bhatia, Ci=
ti=E2=80=99s head of spread products. =E2=80=9CBanks are now looking to cre=
ate more of a syndicated market out of their senior loan book, but you need=
 to get ratings in order to maximise the distribution of these loans.=E2=80=
=9D ...=E2=80=9CThe market has changed. In corporate bond trading the walle=
t [industry revenue pool] has declined sharply since 2020,=E2=80=9D he said=
. =E2=80=9CPrivate financing is where the growth is. These funds are growin=
g and they need leverage, so they come to us for financing.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=A6Bhatia said senior loans to private credit funds attract risk-weighted c=
apital of 20% for banks =E2=80=93 a level he described as =E2=80=9Coptimal=
=E2=80=9D. These financing facilities are typically secured against the ass=
ets of direct lending funds or against the funds themselves. The seniority =
of the loan provides banks with a thick layer of insulation against default=
 in the underlying direct lending portfolios, making it resemble the senior=
 tranche of a mid-market collateralised loan obligation.The rough sorting i=
s:=09Dedicated risk-taking private equity firms own the equity in companies=
.=09Dedicated semi-risk-taking private credit funds own a mezzanine tranche=
 of the companies, getting high returns to take credit risk.=09Banks and th=
e bond market own the senior tranche, getting low returns in exchange for p=
roviding much of the money but not taking too much risk.Elsewhere in privat=
e credit, the Bank for International Settlements published its Annual Econo=
mic Report in June, with a box on =E2=80=9Cthe challenge of private credit.=
=E2=80=9D There are concerns about incentives:The close links of private cr=
edit with private equity raise questions about the incentive structures and=
 the existence of proper internal corporate controls. For instance, in the =
United States 78% of private credit deal volume goes to private equity spon=
sored firms. Private credit funds have also issued loans to private equity =
funds collateralised with the funds=E2=80=99 underlying portfolio of compan=
ies. These so-called net asset value loans can have a variety of purposes, =
such as for bridge financing. However, they are also being used to accelera=
te distributions to private equity investors. While fund managers often inv=
est their own capital in the vehicle (=E2=80=9Cskin in the game=E2=80=9D), =
signalling the compatibility of managers=E2=80=99 incentives with investors=
=E2=80=99 interests, as many as 40% of the funds do not feature skin in the=
 game (Graph D1.B. light blue bar). This suggests scope for incentive misal=
ignment in a substantial segment of the sector.Risks to financial stability=
 from private credit warrant close monitoring. Mitigating factors include t=
he still small size, low share in investors=E2=80=99 portfolios, low liquid=
ity risks and low fund-level leverage. However, the direct and indirect int=
erconnections with other parts of the financial system, especially banks, c=
ould amplify future shocks. Private credit is connected to the banking sect=
or at least through: (i) contingent credit lines that banks provide; (ii) j=
oint ventures, in which some banks originate and distribute the underlying =
portfolio asset while retaining skin in the game; and (iii) interest rate h=
edging, where banks serve as counterparties to firms seeking to hedge their=
 floating-rate liabilities to private credit funds.I suppose =E2=80=9Cthe c=
lose links of private credit with private equity raise questions about the =
incentive structures and the existence of proper internal corporate control=
s=E2=80=9D means something like =E2=80=9Cit is weird that the same big priv=
ate equity firms that write the equity checks for all the buyouts are now a=
lso writing the debt checks, and there are some obvious potential conflicts=
.=E2=80=9D If a=C2=A0company runs into trouble, and it has both private equ=
ity owners and private credit lenders from overlapping firms, how do they c=
arve up the value? =E2=80=9CFerociously,=E2=80=9D is probably the answer. O=
r maybe =E2=80=9Cby taking as much value as possible from the banks providi=
ng the senior leverage.=E2=80=9D
