<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Paramount</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/35988734.221411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDctMDgvcGFyYW1vdW50LWFncmVlcy10by1za3lkYW5jZS1tZ=
XJnZXItbWFya2luZy1lbmQtdG8tcmVkc3RvbmUtZXJhP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MDgyNF9NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDc=
wOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBecc16c36" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">it is</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Paramount Global=
 agreed to merge with Skydance Media in a deal that hands control of the st=
oried Hollywood studio to producer David Ellison, ending one of the industr=
y=E2=80=99s most dramatic acquisitions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As =
part of the complicated deal months in the making, Paramount Chair Shari Re=
dstone agreed to sell her family=E2=80=99s National Amusements Inc., which =
controls about 77% of the voting stock in Paramount, for $2.4 billion, acco=
rding to a statement released by the company Sunday.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The accord marks an abrupt turnaround after talks between Redston=
e and Ellison, the son of Oracle Corp. co-founder Larry Ellison, collapsed =
last month. Redstone=E2=80=99s decision at the time to end discussions shoc=
ked the board and frustrated employees and investors, sending the stock tum=
bling.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Ellison family and RedBird=
 Capital Partners have agreed to invest more than $8 billion in the busines=
s. That includes $1.5 billion to help pay down Paramount=E2=80=99s debt and=
 $4.5 billion to buy Paramount shares.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">I suppose you can think of this deal as having three main parts:</=
p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0=
;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The Skydance investors buy National=
 Amusements to get control of Paramount. National Amusements <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35988734.221411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODEzODI4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyNDE=
wNTAyNi9kNTU4ODE3ZGRlZjE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1cc093dd" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>owns roughly 10% of the stock of Paramount</a>, but Paramount has two shar=
e classes: Class A stock, which has voting rights, and Class B, which doesn=
=E2=80=99t. And National Amusements owns=C2=A0roughly 77% of the voting Cla=
ss A stock.=C2=A0So the Skydance consortium pays Redstone $2.4 billion for =
National Amusements, and it gets voting control of Paramount.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Paramount then acquires Skydance: Paramount wil=
l merge with Skydance, giving Skydance some shares of new Paramount. This d=
eal values Skydance at $4.75 billion, and Skydance gets paid in new (nonvot=
ing)=C2=A0Paramount stock at $15 per share.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The Skydance investors also kick in another $6 billion of cash to=
 buy Paramount shares: They buy $1.5 billion of stock (nonvoting stock at $=
15 per share) directly from Paramount to strengthen the balance sheet, and =
another $4.5 billion from Paramount=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shareholders. The $4.5 b=
illion goes first to=C2=A0non-Redstone holders of=C2=A0<em>voting=C2=A0</em=
>Paramount shares, at=C2=A0$23 per share, for a total of up to $211 million=
, though they can choose to roll over into new Paramount stock instead. (In=
 which case they will get 1.53=C2=A0nonvoting Class B shares of the new com=
pany per Class A share of the old company: In any case, the Skydance invest=
ors will end up with 100% of the voting stock.)=C2=A0And then the rest of t=
he cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0about $4.3 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0goes to=C2=A0buyin=
g=C2=A0<em>nonvoting </em>Class B shares at $15 per share. If every Paramou=
nt shareholder elects cash, then only about 43% of them will get cashed out=
.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tran=
sparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The rest will keep their nonvoting Class B stock in the new Param=
ount. As of noon today, Paramount=E2=80=99s Class B shares were trading aro=
und=C2=A0$11.47, so presumably everyone will elect cash and get prorated.</=
li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those elements are sort of in declinin=
g order of importance. Step 1 is really the main thing: You can=E2=80=99t d=
o anything with Paramount without Shari Redstone=E2=80=99s voting shares, a=
nd that means buying her out at a premium. And then=C2=A0buying out Redston=
e gives you control of Paramount. If you want to take over Paramount, make =
yourself chief executive officer and generally take control of its strategy=
, buying a block of 77% of the voting stock gets you most of the way there.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Step 2 is also important to making the=
 deal make sense for Skydance: They want to integrate their company with Pa=
ramount. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35988=
734.221411/aHR0cHM6Ly9pci5wYXJhbW91bnQuY29tL3N0YXRpYy1maWxlcy9mMDZjNGYwOC0w=
MTk4LTRjMjUtYWQ1MC0xNWY0MDcxYjZlZjg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2acade6c" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">investor presentation</a> touts the benefits of =E2=80=9Cunification of=
 marquee rights=E2=80=9D (because Paramount and Skydance co-produce various=
 franchises like Top Gun, Mission: Impossible and Star Trek) and transition=
ing =E2=80=9Cto a world-class media and technology enterprise.=E2=80=9D Als=
o it is optically appealing for this deal to involve a merger of two actual=
 content companies, instead of just a group of investors taking over Paramo=
unt without paying for all of the shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A=
nd Step 3 is important to getting the deal through a special committee of i=
ndependent Paramount directors. The deal makes sense for Redstone and Skyda=
nce with only Steps 1 and 2: Redstone would get her cash, and Skydance woul=
d get its merger and its control of Paramount, without paying any of Paramo=
unt=E2=80=99s other shareholders anything. But Paramount=E2=80=99s board of=
 directors has fiduciary obligations to the nonvoting shareholders, and it =
wants them to get something too. Cashing out=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of them=
 at a premium would be too big an ask, but cashing out=C2=A0<em>almost half=
=C2=A0</em>of their stock, at a premium, is a compromise the board can live=
 with. =E2=80=9CWe are pleased to have reached an agreement that we believe=
 delivers to Paramount stockholders both immediate value and future upside =
opportunity,=E2=80=9D said <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/35988734.221411/aHR0cHM6Ly9pci5wYXJhbW91bnQuY29tL25ld3MtcmVsZWFzZX=
MvbmV3cy1yZWxlYXNlLWRldGFpbHMvcGFyYW1vdW50LWdsb2JhbHMtc3BlY2lhbC1jb21taXR0Z=
WUtdW5hbmltb3VzbHktYXBwcm92ZXMtbWVyZ2Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd0140ecc" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">the special committee</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhil=
e Redstone is getting roughly $2.4 billion for National Amusements (includi=
ng debt), <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35988734=
.221411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODE=
zODI4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyNDEwNTAyNi9kNTU4ODE3ZGRlZjE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cC1cc093dd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">which owns</a> about 31.5 million Class A shares a=
nd about 32 million Class B shares. At the deal prices ($23 per Class A sha=
re, $15 per Class B), National Amusements=E2=80=99 stake in Paramount is wo=
rth about $1.2 billion. The extra $1.2 billion presumably accounts for Nati=
onal Amusements=E2=80=99 chain of movie theaters, which are worth something=
. But it also presumably accounts for=C2=A0an extra premium for Redstone, w=
ho is essential to the deal, and whose Class A shares are just worth <em>mo=
re=C2=A0</em>than everyone else=E2=80=99s. The other Class A shareholders h=
ave=C2=A0votes, but she has the votes that matter.</p><table class=3D"livei=
ntent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"=
>
